content: Had a coffee with an old friend from college. He's now working on AI for finance. Got me thinking about how I could use my coding skills to make something... innovative.
Diving into research on AI assistants. The potential to create something that learns, adapts, and helps with daily tasks is intriguing.
Just started coding my own AI agent. It's basic now, but I'm excited to see where this goes.
Progress! My AI can now recognize basic voice commands. Next up, making it more responsive and personable.
Decided to name my AI project "Xander". Feels right. Now, to give Xander some personality.
Xander's learning curve is steep, but he's getting there. Just made him respond with a bit of humor.
Hit a snag with Xander's memory function. It's like trying to teach a robot to remember. Back to the drawing board.
Met with a potential investor. Pitched Xander as a personal assistant that learns from you. Fingers crossed!
Xander's now capable of basic chat. It's like talking to a very polite, slightly confused robot.
Discovered a new Rust library that could speed up Xander's processing. Time to refactor.
Xander's now running on my local machine. It's slow, but it's mine.
Joined a NYC tech meetup. Shared Xander's progress, got some great feedback. Feeling motivated.
Xander's first public appearance at the meetup was a hit. He even managed a few witty replies.
Got an offer to collaborate with a local startup on integrating Xander into their app. This could be big.
